===Etymology===
From Latin '''[[#Latin|synecdoche]]''', from Greek [[συνεκδοχή]] (sunekdokhe)

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/sɪˈnɛkdəki/ ''or'' /sɪ'nɛkdoʊki/}}
*{{SAMPA|/sI"nEkd@ki/}}
*{{audio|en-us-synecdoche.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Alternative spellings===
*[[syndoche]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[metaphor]] by which an inclusive term stands for something included, or vice versa; A metaphor in which a part is spoken of as the whole (hand for laborer) or vice-versa (the court for the judge).

====Examples====
:*''fifty head of cattle'' — part (head) for whole (animal).
:*''the police knocked down my door'' — whole (the police) for part (some police officers)
:*''put it on the plastic'' — material (plastic) for object (credit card)
:*''the cat stalks the gazelle'' — class (cat) for subclass (e.g., leopard)
:*''hand me a Kleenex&reg;'' — subclass (brand named product) for class (all similar products)

